	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Yes, &quot;up&quot; to enter a doors seems to work fine.<br /><br />I've managed to setup CHRRAM and bank-switching. (using the codeseg and rodataseg pragmas of cc65)<br />Here's an example of calling a function from another bank:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&nbsp; Switch(1);<br />&nbsp; Bank1Test(1,2,3);<br />&nbsp; Switch(3);<br /></div><br />This works... (at least if I call Bank1Test(); from bank 3, the fixed bank)<br />It looks a bit complicated, though. Is there an easier way? How do you handle the banks?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>calima</b> [ Sun Sep 03, 2017 11:14 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Progress Thread - Wolfling</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The latest cc65 version includes support for trampolines, added by me, which make for transparent bankswitching.<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">// header<br />#pragma wrapped-call(push, trampoline, 1)<br />void Bank1Test(char a, char b, char c);<br />#pragma wrapped-call(pop)<br /><br />// C file<br />Bank1Test(1,2,3);</div><br /><br />It stacks and even allows for code in a switchable bank to call code in another switchable bank, returning to where things were afterwards (if you write your trampoline to do so, of course).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


